{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13880"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13880"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.03,0.05,0.62,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102190"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6497"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13880"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84654"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"318"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1330"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2238"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4608"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44602"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102190"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of worsening shortness of breath and acute onset confusion. He has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes and a recent diagnosis of prostate cancer, for which he is currently being managed by a urologist. His regular medications include metformin, olmesartan and amlodipine. He is a lifetime non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 88% on room air, temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is started on supplementary oxygen. The chest is clear on auscultation. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with a new right bundle branch block and T wave inversions in V1-V4. A bedside echocardiogram reveals a dilated right ventricle with reduced function and bowing of the interventricular septum into the left ventricle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing an initial fluid bolus of 250mL of normal saline, his blood pressure improves to 104/65mmHg, although he remains tachycardic at 118/min. Oxygen is applied via Hudson mask with improvement in saturations to 95% on 6L/min, but remains tachypnoeic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer 1000mls of intravenous normal saline over 15 minutes","Order D-dimer","Administer 40 mg of intravenous furosemide","Arrange urgent CT pulmonary angiogram","Order troponin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMassive pulmonary embolism (PE) can lead to different types of shock. Initially, it causes obstructive shock due to the mechanical obstruction of pulmonary blood flow. This can rapidly progress to cardiogenic shock as the right ventricle fails under the increased afterload. The combination of these mechanisms results in systemic hypoperfusion, which can manifest as hypotension, tachycardia, and end-organ dysfunction such as confusion. Recognition of these shock states is crucial for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe echocardiogram findings of right ventricular dilatation, reduced function, and interventricular septal bowing are significant indicators of right heart strain. These findings suggest severe hemodynamic compromise and are consistent with a massive PE. Right heart strain on echocardiogram is associated with increased mortality in PE and helps identify patients who may benefit from more aggressive interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with signs and symptoms consistent with shock secondary to a massive pulmonary embolism (PE). The most appropriate first step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Earrange urgent CT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because the underlying cause of the shock needs to be confirmed promptly to guide appropriate treatment. Confirming the diagnosis of PE is essential before initiating high-risk interventions such as thrombolysis. Rapid action is crucial in this scenario, as delays in diagnosis and treatment can lead to increased morbidity and mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering 1000mls of intravenous normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E over 15 minutes would not be appropriate in this case. While fluid resuscitation is often a first-line treatment in other types of shock, patients with right ventricular failure due to PE may have limited ability to accommodate additional preload, and excessive fluid could worsen right ventricular distension. He has been given a small fluid bolus with some improvement in blood pressure, further fluids should be used with caution and in small increments with consideration of early commencement of vasopressors so as to exacerbate cardiovascular collapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering a D-dimer\u003C/strong\u003E test might be considered as part of the diagnostic workup for PE, but it should not be the first step in this scenario. In a patient with high clinical suspicion of haemodynamically unstable PE, waiting for D-dimer results could delay crucial treatment. Moreover, D-dimer can be elevated in many conditions and is not specific enough to guide immediate management in this critical situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in this setting. The patient is already hypotensive, and diuresis could further compromise blood pressure and tissue perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering troponin\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate first step in this case. While elevated troponin levels can be seen in massive PE due to right ventricular strain, waiting for these results would delay definitive diagnosis and treatment. The clinical picture and bedside echocardiogram findings already strongly suggest PE, and immediate imaging is more crucial for confirming the diagnosis and guiding management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with suspected massive PE, prompt diagnosis is crucial for guiding appropriate management, which may include thrombolysis, catheter-directed therapies, or surgical embolectomy. Therefore, arranging an urgent CT pulmonary angiogram is the most appropriate first step, as it allows for immediate diagnosis and helps determine the most suitable treatment strategy. This rapid diagnostic approach is essential in potentially life-threatening situations where timely intervention can significantly impact patient outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is, as always, important to consider patient safety prior to transporting to imaging, and in a haemodynamically unstable patient it is often essential to first gain stability prior to transporting them out of a resuscitation area for a lengthy scan. As this patient has had improvement with small intervention, it is safe to do so but deterioration plans should be discussed and communicated with all team members prior to patient transport.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Massive pulmonary embolism can cause both obstructive shock and cardiogenic shock secondary to acute right ventricular failure.","Prompt diagnosis with CT pulmonary angiogram is crucial in suspected massive pulmonary embolism to guide appropriate management, which may include thrombolysis, catheter-directed therapies, or surgical embolectomy.","Confirming the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism is essential before initiating high-risk interventions such as thrombolysis.","Right heart strain on echocardiogram is a significant finding in massive pulmonary embolism, indicating severe hemodynamic compromise."],"references":["Kucher N, Goldhaber SZ. Management of Massive Pulmonary Embolism. Circulation. 2005;112(2):e28-e32. Available at: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.105.551374","Kruger PC, Eikelboom JW, Douketis JD, Hankey GJ. Pulmonary embolism: update on diagnosis and management. Med J Aust. 2019 Jul;211(2):82-87. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31216072/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84654"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13880"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84654"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T09:52:0